TY  - JOUR
T1  - Technology Conglomeration, Strategic Alliances, and Corporate Innovation
AU  - Li, Kai
AU  - Qiu, Jiaping
AU  - Wang, Jin
Y1  - 2019/03/19
PY  - 2019
DA  - 2019/11/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2018.3085
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2018.3085
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 5065
EP  - 5090
VL  - 65
IS  - 11
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We examine the organizational choice and innovative activity of technology conglomerates?firms that explore different technology fields with heated inventive activity. We develop a measure of firm-to-economy technological proximity to capture the extent of a firm?s technology conglomeration. We show that technology conglomerates are more likely to form alliances and that these alliances lead to higher patent output. In terms of underlying mechanisms, we show that after alliance formation, there are significant knowledge pooling and cross-fertilization between technology conglomerates and their alliance partners. Moreover, technology conglomerates produce more patents that are novel and/or with greater impact. Our findings suggest that both synergy and tolerance for failure are important motives for technology conglomerates to use alliances to accelerate corporate innovation.This paper was accepted by Gustavo Manso, finance.
AB  - We examine the organizational choice and innovative activity of technology conglomerates?firms that explore different technology fields with heated inventive activity. We develop a measure of firm-to-economy technological proximity to capture the extent of a firm?s technology conglomeration. We show that technology conglomerates are more likely to form alliances and that these alliances lead to higher patent output. In terms of underlying mechanisms, we show that after alliance formation, there are significant knowledge pooling and cross-fertilization between technology conglomerates and their alliance partners. Moreover, technology conglomerates produce more patents that are novel and/or with greater impact. Our findings suggest that both synergy and tolerance for failure are important motives for technology conglomerates to use alliances to accelerate corporate innovation.This paper was accepted by Gustavo Manso, finance.
